57: /**
58:  * A CompletedCheckpoint describes a checkpoint after all required tasks acknowledged it (with their
59:  * state) and that is considered successful. The CompletedCheckpoint class contains all the metadata
60:  * of the checkpoint, i.e., checkpoint ID, timestamps, and the handles to all states that are part
61:  * of the checkpoint.
62:  *
63:  * <h2>Size the CompletedCheckpoint Instances</h2>
64:  *
65:  * <p>In most cases, the CompletedCheckpoint objects are very small, because the handles to the
66:  * checkpoint states are only pointers (such as file paths). However, the some state backend
67:  * implementations may choose to store some payload data directly with the metadata (for example to
68:  * avoid many small files). If those thresholds are increased to large values, the memory
69:  * consumption of the CompletedCheckpoint objects can be significant.
70:  *
71:  * <h2>Metadata Persistence</h2>
72:  *
73:  * <p>The metadata of the CompletedCheckpoint is also persisted in an external storage system.
74:  * Checkpoints have an external pointer, which points to the metadata. For example when storing a
75:  * checkpoint in a file system, that pointer is the file path to the checkpoint's folder or the
76:  * metadata file. For a state backend that stores metadata in database tables, the pointer could be
77:  * the table name and row key. The pointer is encoded as a String.
78:  */
79: @NotThreadSafe
80: public class CompletedCheckpoint implements Serializable, Checkpoint {
81: 
82:     private static final Logger LOG = LoggerFactory.getLogger(CompletedCheckpoint.class);
83: 
84:     private static final long serialVersionUID = -8360248179615702014L;
